   <abstract>Computational Resilience is the process of maintaining the correctness and efficiency of computing systems in the presence of faults. Resilience is increasingly becoming a major issue for systems running Large Scale High-Performance applications. These systems consist of millions of processors and run billions of threads, and this makes them susceptible to various types of faults. The time taken to perform Application Level Checkpoint and Restart, which is the current approach to resilience, is approaching the mean time to failure of these systems. There is a critical need for new approaches to fault tolerance for the current Exascale systems and systems of the future.\\~\\Monte Carlo Methods are intrinsically suited to High-Performance Computing and can be applied to a variety of problems. They are stochastic methods that involve numerous independent computations that scale quite linearly. These programs are affected by several types of faults including Single Event Upsets, hardware failures, and software faults. In this work, we simulate exascale machines running Monte Carlo applications and observe their performance and behavior in the presence of faults. Faults are injected into the system in a controlled fashion and the propagation of the errors introduced by the faults are recorded. This information can be used to analyze the consequences of faults and to mitigate and constrain the effects of unpredictable faults. Observing the propagation of faulty calculations, it was determined that it is possible to complete calculations that would have otherwise stopped and restarted several times, within an acceptable error bound.</abstract>
